{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":1369,"record_hash":"sha256:22f2440d2b49e9507f42a033aa975dcbf59c6c5a8d8c3d7ed73fadc6b0e30342","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:31:46.635Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 7c9511\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1223\nOutput:\ncapture project.\n\n### 1. Session Handoff\n\nHandoff wants enough project-scoped session context to continue work on another\nmachine or with another agent. For this use case, capture turns help because\nthey add structure:\n\n- the session can be reconstructed as a sequence of user/agent interactions\n- a future reader can see the repository state around each interaction\n- consumers can choose the latest capture turn, a specific capture turn, or a\n  window of turns instead of treating the whole transcript as one flat blob\n\nHandoff does not necessarily need branch association. It mostly needs readable\nconversation records, ordering, and enough environment context to orient the\nnext agent.\n\n### 2. Review Sharing\n\nReview sharing wants a GitButler web view that can show reviewers what happened\nbehind a branch or pull request:\n\n- prompts\n- assistant responses\n- tool calls\n- planning depth\n- discussed edge cases\n- follow-up questions\n\nFor this use case, capture turns are more valuable than whole-session links\nbecause a session may span unrelated work. A review view can start from a\nbranch, change, or PR, find related sessions, and then use turn evidence to\nhighlight the likely relevant parts of those sessions. Commit-centric lookup can\ncome later by resolving through change or branch evidence; it does not need its\nown v1 index.\n\nThe important line remains: capture turns can provide evidence and suggestions\nwithout automatically asserting durable ownership.\n\n## Proposed Hierarchy\n\nThe broader data hierarchy becomes:\n\n```text\none session -> many capture turns -> many records\n```\n\nA session remains the durable project-scoped object. A capture turn represents\none capture invocation, usually one observed agent stop-hook run. Transcript\nrecords remain the normalized conversation/tool events that `but-agentlog`\nalready stores and deduplicates.\n\nThis is deliberately not:\n\n```text\nbranch -> session -> records\n```\n\nBranches, \n[TRUNCATED]\nscript\nrecord. An environment-only observation should not create a capture turn.\nOtherwise the model drifts from agent-session capture into repository telemetry.\n\nThe first hook run for a session may capture more than one actual conversation\nturn if it imports an existing transcript backlog. Later stop-hook runs should\nusually map more closely to one user/agent interaction. That distinction should\nstay visible in the model: a capture turn is a capture observation, not\nnecessarily a provider-native turn.\n\nFor first-time backfill, create one capture turn containing all newly written\nrecords and one environment snapshot from capture time. Provider-native turn\nidentifiers, when available, can be preserved as optional record-level grouping\nmetadata, but they should not become real capture turns during backfill because\nhistorical repository environment snapshots cannot be reconstructed.\n\nStore a compact `capture_kind` on the capture turn:\n\n- `backfill`: the capture imported an existing transcript backlog\n- `incremental`: the capture observed new records from an ongoing session\n\nBackfill turns are valid transcript history, but their environment snapshot is\nweaker association evidence because it only describes capture time, not the time\neach historical provider turn happened.\n\nBackfill must still be readable. Record parsing should preserve enough grouping\nmetadata for handoff and review UIs to render logical conversation turns inside\nthe backfill capture turn:\n\n- provider turn key when the source provides one\n- otherwise a derived display group based on user-message boundaries and record\n  order\n\n## Capture Turn Data\n\nA capture turn needs a stable ID for idempotent repeated capture. Given a\ncapture turn, it should be possible to find the transcript records that were\nnewly observed in that turn.\n\nCapture turn identity should be derived from capture content, not from time or\nprovider turn ids. Use a 128-bit truncated SHA-256 value: take the first 16\nbytes of the digest and render them as 32 lowercase hex characters.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:31:46.635Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}